<!doctype html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">

    <!-- Always force latest IE rendering engine or request Chrome Frame -->
    <meta content="IE=edge,chrome=1" http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible">

    <!-- Use title if it's in the page YAML frontmatter -->
    <title><%= current_page.data.title || "The Middleman" %></title>

    <%= stylesheet_link_tag "all" %>
    <%= javascript_include_tag  "all" %>
  </head>
  
<header>
	<div class="container">
		<h1>Practical Color Theory for People Who Code</h1>
		</div>
		<h3>Natalya Shelburne
		<br>
		<a href="https://twitter.com/natalyathree">@natalyathree</a></h3>
</header>
<div class="hero">
	<div class="container">
	<div class="half">
		<h1>Prerequisites</h1>
		<p>Sass color functions give you the same creative power as owning a set of paints, brushes, and canvas. My goal is to demystify design decisions and reveal them to be logical, predictable, and driven by principles that anyone interested can learn.</p>
		<h4>New to this? Check out these resources first</h4>
		<ul class="text-list-item-box">
			<li><a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-color/#hsl-color">CSS Color Module Level 3: HSL</a></li>
			<li><a href="http://hslpicker.com/">Most Excellent HSL color picker</a></li>
			<li><a href="http://jackiebalzer.com/color">Interactive Sass Color Functions</a></li>
			<li><a href="http://sass-lang.com/documentation/Sass/Script/Functions.html#hsla-instance_method">Read the Sass-lang Docs</a></li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	<div class="half">
			<h1>Design Decisions and Patterns</h1>
			<p> "The advantage of HSL over RGB is that it is far more intuitive: you can guess at the colors you want, and then tweak. It is also easier to create sets of matching colors (by keeping the hue the same and varying the lightness/darkness, and saturation). Plus, it is trivial to convert HSL to RGB."</p>
		<a href="#start" class="cta-button">Let's get started!</a>

	</div>
	</div>
</div>

  <body class="<%= page_classes %>">
    <%= yield %>
  </body>
</html>
